evaluation.response:
Absolutely—happy to help. To give you a precise refactor, please paste:
- The function (or the relevant parts)
- Any helpers it calls
- A flaky test and the failure you see
- Node version and test runner (Jest/Mocha), plus libs (e.g., axios, knex)

If you can’t share code, here’s a quick, proven refactor recipe that also fixes most flaky tests.

Refactor recipe (functional core + imperative shell)
- Extract pure logic: Move all branching/calculation/validation into pure functions with no I/O.
- Inject dependencies: Pass in DB/API clients, clock, RNG, logger, config as parameters.
- Isolate side effects: DB, HTTP, file I/O, env reads, Date.now, Math.random.
- Make async explicit: Always return/await Promises; no fire-and-forget.
- Deterministic time/random: Inject clock and RNG so tests control them.
- Idempotency and error handling: Small, clear functions with explicit errors and no shared mutable state.

Example before (does too much)
async function processOrder(id) {
  const order = await db.orders.findById(id);
  if (!order) throw new Error('NotFound');

  if (order.status !== 'PENDING') return order;

  const total = calcTotal(order.items); // also logs internally
  const charge = await axios.post(process.env.PAY_URL, { amount: total });

  order.txId = charge.data.id;
  order.status = 'PAID';
  await db.orders.update(order);

  await email.send(order.userEmail, 'Thanks!', buildEmailBody(order));
  return order;
}

Refactor after (testable)
function decideNextState({ order, total, chargeId }) {
  if (!order) throw new Error('NotFound');
  if (order.status !== 'PENDING') return { kind: 'noop', order };
  return {
    kind: 'update',
    next: { ...order, txId: chargeId, status: 'PAID' }
  };
}

function calculateTotal(items) {
  // pure math
  return items.reduce((s, i) => s + i.price * i.qty, 0);
}

// Orchestrator with injected deps
async function processOrder({ repo, payments, mailer, clock }, id) {
  const order = await repo.get(id);
  if (!order) throw new Error('NotFound');

  if (order.status !== 'PENDING') return order;

  const total = calculateTotal(order.items);
  const chargeId = await payments.charge({ amount: total, orderId: id, at: clock.now() });

  const decision = decideNextState({ order, total, chargeId });
  if (decision.kind === 'noop') return decision.order;

  const saved = await repo.update(decision.next);
  await mailer.send(saved.userEmail, 'Thanks!', buildEmailBody(saved));
  return saved;
}

Wiring in production
const processOrderProd = (id) =>
  processOrder(
    {
      repo: realRepo,
      payments: realPayments,
      mailer: realMailer,
      clock: { now: () => Date.now() }
    },
    id
  );

Unit tests (Jest) – deterministic and fast
- Test pure functions directly:
  expect(calculateTotal([...])).toBe(1234)
  expect(decideNextState(...)).toEqual(...)

- Test orchestrator with fakes/mocks:
  const repo = { get: jest.fn(), update: jest.fn() };
  const payments = { charge: jest.fn() };
  const mailer = { send: jest.fn() };
  const clock = { now: () => 1710000000000 };

  repo.get.mockResolvedValue({ id: '1', status: 'PENDING', items: [...] });
  payments.charge.mockResolvedValue('ch_123');
  repo.update.mockImplementation(async x => x);

  const result = await processOrder({ repo, payments, mailer, clock }, '1');

  expect(payments.charge).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ amount: 1234, orderId: '1', at: 1710000000000 });
  expect(mailer.send).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
  expect(result.status).toBe('PAID');

Common sources of flakiness and quick fixes
- Not awaiting async work: Ensure every async call is awaited; avoid unhandled promise rejections.
- Real timers or setTimeout in tests: Prefer injecting clock. If you must, use jest.useFakeTimers(); await flushMicrotasks(); jest.runAllTimers().
- Time/randomness: Inject clock and RNG; never call Date.now/Math.random in core logic.
- Shared state between tests: Reset mocks and singletons in afterEach; avoid module-level caches.
- Network/DB in unit tests: Stub them. If using nock, nock.cleanAll() in afterEach.
- Event listeners and queues: Remove listeners and drain queues in teardown.

If you share your function and a failing test, I’ll refactor it concretely and make the tests reliable.
